{"title_page": "F\u00e9lix Mi\u00e9lli Venerando", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = F\u00e9lix\n| image                = F\u00e9lix Mi\u00e9li Venerando.jpg\n| image_size           = 190\n| caption              = F\u00e9lix in 2008\n| fullname             = F\u00e9lix Mi\u00e9li Venerando\n| birth_date           = {{Birth date|df=yes|1937|12|24}}\n| birth_place          = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] ([[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|SP]]), [[Brazil]]\n| death_date           = {{death date and age|df=yes|2012|8|24|1937|12|24}}\n| death_place          = S\u00e3o Paulo (SP), Brazil\n| height               = 1.76 m<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wcwinners.html|title=World Cup Champions Squads 1930 - 2018|website=www.rsssf.com|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n| position             = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| years1  = 1953\u20131955 | clubs1 = [[Clube Atl\u00e9tico Juventus|Juventus]]\n| years2  = 1955\u20131968 | clubs2 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos|Portuguesa]]\n| years3  = 1957\u20131960 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Nacional Atl\u00e9tico Clube (SP)|Nacional (SP)]] (loan)\n| years4  = 1968\u20131976 | clubs4 = [[Fluminense Football Club|Fluminense]]\n| nationalyears1 = 1965\u20131972 | nationalteam1 = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] | nationalcaps1 = 39 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 1982 | managerclubs1 = [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]]\n| manageryears2 = 1982 | managerclubs2 = [[Ava\u00ed Futebol Clube|Ava\u00ed]]\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|Football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{BRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 Mexico]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''F\u00e9lix Mi\u00e9lli Venerando''' (24 December 1937 \u2013 24 August 2012) was a [[Association football|football]] player from [[Brazil]], more commonly known as '''F\u00e9lix'''.<ref>{{cite web |author=ESPN http://espn.estadao.com.br |url=http://espn.estadao.com.br/noticia/277320_morre-ex-goleiro-felix-campeao-do-mundo-com-a-selecao-brasileira-em-1970 |title=Morre ex-goleiro F\u00e9lix, campe\u00e3o do mundo com a sele\u00e7\u00e3o brasileira em 1970 |publisher=Espn.estadao.com.br |date= |access-date=24 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826233341/http://espn.estadao.com.br/noticia/277320_morre-ex-goleiro-felix-campeao-do-mundo-com-a-selecao-brasileira-em-1970 |archive-date=26 August 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19376328|title= Brazil's 1970 goalkeeper Felix dies|date=25 August 2012|work=BBC News|accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n \nF\u00e9lix was born in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]].  He was [[goalkeeper (football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos]] and [[Fluminense Football Club]]. He has 47 caps (8 non-official) with the [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian national team]], including the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]]-winning squad.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Terra Brasil|title=Capit\u00e3o do tri, Torres relembra F\u00e9lix \"extraordin\u00e1rio\" e criticado|url=http://esportes.terra.com.br/futebol/noticias/0,,OI6100528-EI1832,00-Capitao+do+tri+Torres+relembra+Felix+extraordinario+e+criticado.html|language=Portuguese|date=24 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/felix/|title=F\u00e9lix|publisher=worldfootball.net|lang=en|accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''[[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos|Portuguesa]]'''\n* RIO Branco Cup: 1967, 1968 \n* [[Campeonato Carioca]]: [[1969 Campeonato Carioca|1969]], [[1971 Campeonato Carioca|1971]], [[1973 Campeonato Carioca|1973]], [[1975 Campeonato Carioca|1975]], [[1976 Campeonato Carioca|1976]]\n* Campeonato Brasileiro: 1970\n\n===International===\n'''Brazil'''\n* [[FIFA World Cup]]: [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT|17975<!-- /Felix_1 -->}}\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212034848/http://www.sitedalusa.com/ |date=12 February 2007 |title=Sitedalusa.com }}\n\n{{Brazil squad 1970 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas managers}}\n{{Ava\u00ed Futebol Clube managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Felix}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:1970 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:Brazil international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian football managers]]\n[[Category:Clube Atl\u00e9tico Juventus players]]\n[[Category:Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos players]]\n[[Category:Nacional Atl\u00e9tico Clube (SP) players]]\n[[Category:Fluminense FC players]]\n[[Category:Ava\u00ed FC managers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = F\u00e9lix\n| image                = F\u00e9lix Mi\u00e9li Venerando.jpg\n| image_size           = 190\n| caption              = F\u00e9lix in 2008\n| fullname             = F\u00e9lix Mi\u00e9li Venerando\n| birth_date           = {{Birth date|df=yes|1937|12|24}}\n| birth_place          = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] ([[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|SP]]), [[Brazil]]\n| death_date           = {{death date and age|df=yes|2012|8|24|1937|12|24}}\n| death_place          = S\u00e3o Paulo (SP), Brazil\n| height               = 1.76 m<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wcwinners.html|title=World Cup Champions Squads 1930 - 2018|website=www.rsssf.com|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n| position             = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| years1  = 1953\u20131955 | clubs1 = [[Clube Atl\u00e9tico Juventus|Juventus]]\n| years2  = 1955\u20131968 | clubs2 = [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos|Portuguesa]]\n| years3  = 1957\u20131960 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Nacional Atl\u00e9tico Clube (SP)|Nacional (SP)]] (loan)\n| years4  = 1968\u20131976 | clubs4 = [[Fluminense Football Club|Fluminense]]\n| nationalyears1 = 1965\u20131972 | nationalteam1 = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] | nationalcaps1 = 39 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 1982 | managerclubs1 = [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]]\n| manageryears2 = 1982 | managerclubs2 = [[Ava\u00ed Futebol Clube|Ava\u00ed]]\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|Football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{BRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 Mexico]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''F\u00e9lix Mi\u00e9lli Venerando''' (24 December 1937 \u2013 24 August 2012) was a [[sAssiciation football|football]] player from [[Brazil]], more commonly known as '''F\u00e9lix'''.<ref>{{cite web |author=ESPN http://espn.estadao.com.br |url=http://espn.estadao.com.br/noticia/277320_morre-ex-goleiro-felix-campeao-do-mundo-com-a-selecao-brasileira-em-1970 |title=Morre ex-goleiro F\u00e9lix, campe\u00e3o do mundo com a sele\u00e7\u00e3o brasileira em 1970 |publisher=Espn.estadao.com.br |date= |access-date=24 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826233341/http://espn.estadao.com.br/noticia/277320_morre-ex-goleiro-felix-campeao-do-mundo-com-a-selecao-brasileira-em-1970 |archive-date=26 August 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19376328|title= Brazil's 1970 goalkeeper Felix dies|date=25 August 2012|work=BBC News|accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n \nF\u00e9lix was born in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]].  He was [[goalkeeper (football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos]] and [[Fluminense Football Club]]. He has 47 caps (8 non-official) with the [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian national team]], including the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]]-winning squad.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Terra Brasil|title=Capit\u00e3o do tri, Torres relembra F\u00e9lix \"extraordin\u00e1rio\" e criticado|url=http://esportes.terra.com.br/futebol/noticias/0,,OI6100528-EI1832,00-Capitao+do+tri+Torres+relembra+Felix+extraordinario+e+criticado.html|language=Portuguese|date=24 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/felix/|title=F\u00e9lix|publisher=worldfootball.net|lang=en|accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''[[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos|Portuguesa]]'''\n* RIO Branco Cup: 1967, 1968 \n* [[Campeonato Carioca]]: [[1969 Campeonato Carioca|1969]], [[1971 Campeonato Carioca|1971]], [[1973 Campeonato Carioca|1973]], [[1975 Campeonato Carioca|1975]], [[1976 Campeonato Carioca|1976]]\n* Campeonato Brasileiro: 1970\n\n===International===\n'''Brazil'''\n* [[FIFA World Cup]]: [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT|17975<!-- /Felix_1 -->}}\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212034848/http://www.sitedalusa.com/ |date=12 February 2007 |title=Sitedalusa.com }}\n\n{{Brazil squad 1970 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas managers}}\n{{Ava\u00ed Futebol Clube managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Felix}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:1970 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:Brazil international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian football managers]]\n[[Category:Clube Atl\u00e9tico Juventus players]]\n[[Category:Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos players]]\n[[Category:Nacional Atl\u00e9tico Clube (SP) players]]\n[[Category:Fluminense FC players]]\n[[Category:Ava\u00ed FC managers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n", "name_user": "Jonas kam", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%A9lix_Mi%C3%A9lli_Venerando"}
{"title_page": "Skill India", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox project\n| image = Skill India.png\n| country = India\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| ministry = [[Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship|Skill Development and Entrepreneurship]]\n| key_people = \n| launched = {{Start date and age|2015|07|15|df=y}}\n| sponsorship = [[High wings Network marketing]]\n| website = https://www.skillindia.gov.in\n| current_status = Active \n}}\n\n'''Skill India''' or the National Skills Development Mission of India is a campaign launched by [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]]. It is managed by the National Skills Development Corporation of India.\n\n==History==\nSkill India campaign was launched by [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 15 July 2015 to train over 40 [[crore]] people in [[India]] in different skills by 2022.<ref>{{citation |title=Government to train 40 crore people under Skill India initiative |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-07-15/news/64449992_1_skill-india-prime-minister-narendra-modi-skill-training |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=15 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>Hanzala Kathewadi </ref>\n\n==Initiatives==\nVarious initiatives under this campaign are:<ref>{{citation |url=http://ndtv.com/india-news/pm-modi-launches-skill-india-initiative-that-aims-to-train-40-crore-people-781897 |title=PM Modi Launches Skill India Initiative That Aims to Train 40 Crore People |work=[[NDTV]] |date=15 July 2015 }}</ref>\n* National Skill Development Mission\n* National Policy for Skill Development and Entrepreneurship, 2015\n* [[Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojana]] (PMKVY)\n* Skill Loan scheme\n* Rural India Skill\n\n==Partnership concept==\n[[UK]] has entered into a partnership with India under skill India programme. Virtual partnerships will be initiated at the school level to enable young people of these country to experience the school system of the other country and develop an understanding of the culture, traditions and social and family systems. A commitment to achieve mutual recognition of UK and Indian qualifications was made.<ref>{{citation|title=Modi in UK: 11 British companies support skill development in India|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report-modi-in-uk-11-british-companies-support-skill-development-in-india-2144786|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=13 November 2015|agency=[[Asian News International|ANI]]|location=[[London]]}}</ref>\n\n==Skill India Developments==\n\nThe recent systematic literature review conducted by Cabral and Dhar (2019)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cabral|first=Clement|last2=Dhar|first2=Rajib Lochan|date=2019-06-25|title=Skill development research in India: a systematic literature review and future research agenda|journal=Benchmarking: An International Journal|volume=26|issue=7|pages=2242\u20132266|language=en|doi=10.1108/BIJ-07-2018-0211|issn=1463-5771}}</ref> has identified the significance of skill development wherein the implementation of such schemes mitigate poverty, utilize demographic dividend, socio-economic empowerment of under privileged sectors, achieve economic growth, reduce social challenges, and economic inclusion. As far as institutional mechanism is concerned, the National Skill Development Corporation (NSDC), Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship and the scheme - Prime Minister Kaushal Vikas Yojana (PMKVY) have resulted to achieve considerable results, but not achieved the expected outcomes. The study argues the essential requirement of skill development to achieve technology adoption and women empowerment in the country.\n\n[[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] on 12 February 2016 announced that it will build a new 2.8 million sq. ft. campus in [[Bengaluru]] will be Oracle's largest outside of its headquarters in [[Redwood Shores]], [[California]].<ref name=\"live\">{{citation |title=After Digital India, Oracle seeks to participate in Make in India, Start-up India |url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/NIK7XM3p7ochGKFtDruhUL/After-Digital-India-Oracle-seeks-to-participate-in-Make-in.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=13 February 2016 }}</ref> [[Oracle Academy]] will launch an initiative to train more than half-a-million students each year to develop computer science skills by expanding its partnerships to 2,700 institutions in India from 1,800 at present.<ref name=\"live\" />\n\n[[Japan]]'s private sector is to set up six institutes of manufacturing to train 30,000 people over ten years in Japanese-style manufacturing skills and practices, primarily in the rural areas. Japan-India Institute of Manufacturing (JIM) and Japanese Endowed Courses (JEC) in engineering colleges designated by Japanese companies in India in cooperation between the public and private sectors would be established for this purpose. The first three institutes would be set up in [[Gujarat]], [[Karnataka]] and [[Rajasthan]] in the summer of 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/japan-to-set-up-skill-development-institutes-in-gujarat-karnataka-and-rajasthan/articleshow/55377055.cms|title=Japan to set up skill development institutes in Gujarat, Karnataka and Rajasthan|newspaper=The Economic Times|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the budget of fiscal year 2017 - 18 the government of India has decided to set aside \u20b9 17,000 crore, the highest ever allocation to this sector, in order to boost the Skill India Mission. At least ten million Indian youth enter the country\u2019s workforce each year, but the employment creation in India has not been able to absorb this influx, making increasing unemployment a severe problem. Through this allocation the government aims at generating employment and providing livelihood to the millions of young Indians who enter the work force every year.\n\nThe government has invested \u20b9 4000 crore in the launch of SANKALP (Skill Acquisition and Knowledge Awareness for Livelihood Promotion Programme), another big initiative under the Skill India Mission. Through this it aims at providing market relevant training to 350 million young Indians. Apart from this, the government would set up 100 India International Skills Centres that will conduct advanced courses in foreign languages to help youngsters prepare for overseas jobs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/to-boost-skill-india-mission-govt-sets-aside-rs-17000-crore-in-budget/articleshow/56944089.cms|title= To boost Skill India Mission, Govt sets aside Rs 17,000 crore in Budget|newspaper=The Economic Times|access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref>\nIt provides opportunities to the youth of India.\n\n== Skill Development For Women ==\nRecognition of woman\u2019s role in the field of entrepreneurship in a male dominated arena becomes inevitable.  Till now the social fabric for gender biasness towards women and discriminatory behaviour by the society has remained unchanged. According to  CSO, 59.30% rural women are self-employed and male ratio is 54.50%. This clearly indicates that the government has been undertaking proactive steps to converge the entrepreneurship in India towards development of rural women. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Verma|first=Bhavna|date=2015|title=CHALLENGES OF SKILL DEVELOPMENT AND RURAL WOMEN ENTREPRENEURSHIP|url=http://rdmodernresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/193.pdf|journal=International Journal of Multidisciplinary Research and Modern Education (IJMRME)|volume=1|pages=10|via=}}</ref>  Through the 2<sup>nd</sup> phase of Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojana, around 68.12 lakhs of women had undergone skill training. And also, around 4.08 lakh women had undergone training during 2018-2020, and Industrial training Institutes (ITI) had completed training for 38.72 lakhs women. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Pandey|first=Mahendra|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/international-womens-day-girl-education-literacy-rate-india-6299564/|title=Skill her, skill India: Policy must enable every woman to achieve her potential|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Indian Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe main hurdles that rural women typically faces to attain skill development includes socio-economic problems, political, etc. Apart from that, other challenges includes the different social norms for decision making thus leading to lack of confidence among them, financial constraints and lack of infrastructure creates a gap in training and development opportunities for rural women. so skill development for rural women is required to make them self sufficient and to improve social and economic status. Despite cultural and social constraints restricts women towards the path of entrepreneurship, collective efforts of village panchayats, NGO's, and families are necessary to ensure their employability. Hence the convergence of government and civic society is a must to ensure the improvement of quality of life of such vulnerable groups in Indian society.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Performance==\nAs of 15 February 2016, the \"Indian Leather Development Programme\" trained 51,216 youth in a span of 100 days and it plans to train 1,44,000 young persons annually. Four new branches of \"Footwear Design & Development Institute\" \u2014 at [[Hyderabad]], [[Patna]], [[Banur]] ([[Punjab]]) and [[Ankleshwar]] ([[Gujarat]]) \u2014 are being set up to improve training infrastructure. The industry is undergoing acute skill shortage and most of the people trained are being absorbed by the industry.<ref name=et>{{citation |title=Why Make in India may be the answer to India's unemployment puzzle |url=http://economictimes.com/jobs/why-make-in-india-may-be-the-answer-to-indias-unemployment-puzzle/articleshow/51002694.cms |first1=Rica|last1=Bhattacharyya|first2=Prachi|last2=Verma|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn an endeavour to prepare a generation of skilled employees and leaders in alignment with the modern day market demands, Skill India was launched by Prime Minister Narendra Modi in 2015. Skill India, launched to train over 40 crore citizens with different industry relevant skills by 2022, is to be implemented through a streamlined institutional.<ref name=et />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://skillindia.gov.in Skill India] \n* [http://www.skilldevelopment.gov.in Ministry of Skill Development And Entrepreneurship]\n* [http://msde.gov.in Ministry of Skill Development And Entrepreneurship]\n* [http://www.nsda.gov.in National Skill Development Agency]\n*[https://www.subhe.com/blog/2020/01/02/future-of-skill-based-training-and-development-in-india/ Future Of Skill Based Training And Development In India]\n\n{{Government Schemes in India}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox project\n| image = Skill India.png\n| country = India\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| ministry = [[Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship|Skill Development and Entrepreneurship]]\n| key_people = \n| launched = {{Start date and age|2015|07|15|df=y}}\n| sponsorship = [[High wings Network marketing]]\n| website = https://www.skillindia.gov.in\n| current_status = Active \n}}\n\n'''Skill India''' or the National Skills Development Mission of India, is a campaign launched by [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]]\n\n==History==\nSkill India campaign was launched by [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 15 July 2015 to train over 40 [[crore]] people in [[India]] in different skills by 2022.<ref>{{citation |title=Government to train 40 crore people under Skill India initiative |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-07-15/news/64449992_1_skill-india-prime-minister-narendra-modi-skill-training |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=15 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>Hanzala Kathewadi </ref>\n\n==Initiatives==\nVarious initiatives under this campaign are:<ref>{{citation |url=http://ndtv.com/india-news/pm-modi-launches-skill-india-initiative-that-aims-to-train-40-crore-people-781897 |title=PM Modi Launches Skill India Initiative That Aims to Train 40 Crore People |work=[[NDTV]] |date=15 July 2015 }}</ref>\n* National Skill Development Mission\n* National Policy for Skill Development and Entrepreneurship, 2015\n* [[Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojana]] (PMKVY)\n* Skill Loan scheme\n* Rural India Skill\n\n==Partnership concept==\n[[UK]] has entered into a partnership with India under skill India programme. Virtual partnerships will be initiated at the school level to enable young people of these country to experience the school system of the other country and develop an understanding of the culture, traditions and social and family systems. A commitment to achieve mutual recognition of UK and Indian qualifications was made.<ref>{{citation|title=Modi in UK: 11 British companies support skill development in India|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report-modi-in-uk-11-british-companies-support-skill-development-in-india-2144786|publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=13 November 2015|agency=[[Asian News International|ANI]]|location=[[London]]}}</ref>\n\n==Skill India Developments==\n\nThe recent systematic literature review conducted by Cabral and Dhar (2019)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cabral|first=Clement|last2=Dhar|first2=Rajib Lochan|date=2019-06-25|title=Skill development research in India: a systematic literature review and future research agenda|journal=Benchmarking: An International Journal|volume=26|issue=7|pages=2242\u20132266|language=en|doi=10.1108/BIJ-07-2018-0211|issn=1463-5771}}</ref> has identified the significance of skill development wherein the implementation of such schemes mitigate poverty, utilize demographic dividend, socio-economic empowerment of under privileged sectors, achieve economic growth, reduce social challenges, and economic inclusion. As far as institutional mechanism is concerned, the National Skill Development Corporation (NSDC), Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship and the scheme - Prime Minister Kaushal Vikas Yojana (PMKVY) have resulted to achieve considerable results, but not achieved the expected outcomes. The study argues the essential requirement of skill development to achieve technology adoption and women empowerment in the country.\n\n[[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] on 12 February 2016 announced that it will build a new 2.8 million sq. ft. campus in [[Bengaluru]] will be Oracle's largest outside of its headquarters in [[Redwood Shores]], [[California]].<ref name=\"live\">{{citation |title=After Digital India, Oracle seeks to participate in Make in India, Start-up India |url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/NIK7XM3p7ochGKFtDruhUL/After-Digital-India-Oracle-seeks-to-participate-in-Make-in.html |work=[[Live Mint]] |date=13 February 2016 }}</ref> [[Oracle Academy]] will launch an initiative to train more than half-a-million students each year to develop computer science skills by expanding its partnerships to 2,700 institutions in India from 1,800 at present.<ref name=\"live\" />\n\n[[Japan]]'s private sector is to set up six institutes of manufacturing to train 30,000 people over ten years in Japanese-style manufacturing skills and practices, primarily in the rural areas. Japan-India Institute of Manufacturing (JIM) and Japanese Endowed Courses (JEC) in engineering colleges designated by Japanese companies in India in cooperation between the public and private sectors would be established for this purpose. The first three institutes would be set up in [[Gujarat]], [[Karnataka]] and [[Rajasthan]] in the summer of 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/japan-to-set-up-skill-development-institutes-in-gujarat-karnataka-and-rajasthan/articleshow/55377055.cms|title=Japan to set up skill development institutes in Gujarat, Karnataka and Rajasthan|newspaper=The Economic Times|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the budget of fiscal year 2017 - 18 the government of India has decided to set aside \u20b9 17,000 crore, the highest ever allocation to this sector, in order to boost the Skill India Mission. At least ten million Indian youth enter the country\u2019s workforce each year, but the employment creation in India has not been able to absorb this influx, making increasing unemployment a severe problem. Through this allocation the government aims at generating employment and providing livelihood to the millions of young Indians who enter the work force every year.\n\nThe government has invested \u20b9 4000 crore in the launch of SANKALP (Skill Acquisition and Knowledge Awareness for Livelihood Promotion Programme), another big initiative under the Skill India Mission. Through this it aims at providing market relevant training to 350 million young Indians. Apart from this, the government would set up 100 India International Skills Centres that will conduct advanced courses in foreign languages to help youngsters prepare for overseas jobs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/to-boost-skill-india-mission-govt-sets-aside-rs-17000-crore-in-budget/articleshow/56944089.cms|title= To boost Skill India Mission, Govt sets aside Rs 17,000 crore in Budget|newspaper=The Economic Times|access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref>\nIt provides opportunities to the youth of India.\n\n== Skill Development For Women ==\nRecognition of woman\u2019s role in the field of entrepreneurship in a male dominated arena becomes inevitable.  Till now the social fabric for gender biasness towards women and discriminatory behaviour by the society has remained unchanged. According to  CSO, 59.30% rural women are self-employed and male ratio is 54.50%. This clearly indicates that the government has been undertaking proactive steps to converge the entrepreneurship in India towards development of rural women. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Verma|first=Bhavna|date=2015|title=CHALLENGES OF SKILL DEVELOPMENT AND RURAL WOMEN ENTREPRENEURSHIP|url=http://rdmodernresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/193.pdf|journal=International Journal of Multidisciplinary Research and Modern Education (IJMRME)|volume=1|pages=10|via=}}</ref>  Through the 2<sup>nd</sup> phase of Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojana, around 68.12 lakhs of women had undergone skill training. And also, around 4.08 lakh women had undergone training during 2018-2020, and Industrial training Institutes (ITI) had completed training for 38.72 lakhs women. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Pandey|first=Mahendra|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/international-womens-day-girl-education-literacy-rate-india-6299564/|title=Skill her, skill India: Policy must enable every woman to achieve her potential|date=March 5, 2020|work=The Indian Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe main hurdles that rural women typically faces to attain skill development includes socio-economic problems, political, etc. Apart from that, other challenges includes the different social norms for decision making thus leading to lack of confidence among them, financial constraints and lack of infrastructure creates a gap in training and development opportunities for rural women. so skill development for rural women is required to make them self sufficient and to improve social and economic status. Despite cultural and social constraints restricts women towards the path of entrepreneurship, collective efforts of village panchayats, NGO's, and families are necessary to ensure their employability. Hence the convergence of government and civic society is a must to ensure the improvement of quality of life of such vulnerable groups in Indian society.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Performance==\nAs of 15 February 2016, the \"Indian Leather Development Programme\" trained 51,216 youth in a span of 100 days and it plans to train 1,44,000 young persons annually. Four new branches of \"Footwear Design & Development Institute\" \u2014 at [[Hyderabad]], [[Patna]], [[Banur]] ([[Punjab]]) and [[Ankleshwar]] ([[Gujarat]]) \u2014 are being set up to improve training infrastructure. The industry is undergoing acute skill shortage and most of the people trained are being absorbed by the industry.<ref name=et>{{citation |title=Why Make in India may be the answer to India's unemployment puzzle |url=http://economictimes.com/jobs/why-make-in-india-may-be-the-answer-to-indias-unemployment-puzzle/articleshow/51002694.cms |first1=Rica|last1=Bhattacharyya|first2=Prachi|last2=Verma|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn an endeavour to prepare a generation of skilled employees and leaders in alignment with the modern day market demands, Skill India was launched by Prime Minister Narendra Modi in 2015. Skill India, launched to train over 40 crore citizens with different industry relevant skills by 2022, is to be implemented through a streamlined institutional.<ref name=et />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://skillindia.gov.in Skill India] \n* [http://www.skilldevelopment.gov.in Ministry of Skill Development And Entrepreneurship]\n* [http://msde.gov.in Ministry of Skill Development And Entrepreneurship]\n* [http://www.nsda.gov.in National Skill Development Agency]\n*[https://www.subhe.com/blog/2020/01/02/future-of-skill-based-training-and-development-in-india/ Future Of Skill Based Training And Development In India]\n\n{{Government Schemes in India}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Ministry of Skill Development and Entrepreneurship]]\n", "name_user": "Cokestunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "added mission", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skill_India"}
{"title_page": "Sarvaiya", "text_new": "{{use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{rewrite|date=February 2020}}\nThe '''Sarvaiya''' also spelled ''Sarvaiyya'', ''Sarvia'', ''Sarwia'' are a [[Rajput]] clan of India, mainly found in [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==History==\n\nAccording to the [[Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency]],The Sarvaiyas come from a branch of the [[Chudasama]]s, who are themselves a branch of the [[Samma (tribe)|Samma Rajput]]s. They ruled over Datha.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=State)|first=Bombay (India :|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&q=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&dq=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&hl=en&ei=E2XRTZ2zE4fKrAeh75XDCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAw#v=snippet&q=SARVAIYA%20CHUDASAMA&f=false|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency ...|date=1884|publisher=Government Central Press|language=en}}</ref> Among other estates that they ruled were [[Amreli]], Hathasnsi, [[Jesar]], [[Datha State|Datha]], [[Vasavad]],<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gujarat (India)|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=dCkbAAAAIAAJ|title=Gujarat State Gazetteers: Amreli|date=1972|publisher=Directorate of Government Print., Stationery and Publications, Gujarat State|language=en}}</ref> Santhli, Chital, [[Savarkundla|Kundla]], [[Bhavnagar|Gohilwad]], Chhatrasa, Chiroda, Chok, Pan, Ranigam,<ref name=c>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=Wr4MAAAAIAAJ&q=SARVAIYA&dq=SARVAIYA&hl=en&ei=qWTRTZWtEIjNrQf1xojDCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC4Q6AEwATgK] Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency, Volume 9, Part 1, 1901</ref> and other estates in [[Kathiawar]].<ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=CIoZAAAAYAAJ&q=SARVAIYA&dq=SARVAIYA&hl=en&ei=Z-PRTfqNGo6zrAexl4SiCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBA] Imperial gazetteer of India , 1908 by Sir William Wilson Hunter, [[Richard Burn (Indologist)|Sir Richard Burn]], Great Britain. India Office</ref>\n\nSarvaiya kingdom like the Chudasamas, were attacked in 1476 by Sultan [[Mahmud Begada]] . When Mahmud Begada, attacked Amreli, after taking over Junagadh from Chudasama, the Sarvaiya rulers of Amreli notably the two brothers Jesaji and Vejaji  for fighting against troops of Sultan Mahmud Begda, became outlaws, in order to re conquer Amreli.  Jesaji and Vejaji were able to get jagir of 64 villages from sultanate of Mohmud Begda  after fighting by remaining in outlawry for twelve years. Subsequently they settled in Hathasni. Later, the brothers divided the new estate between them, Jesoji receiving Hathasni and Vejoji estate of Jesar.<ref name=b>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=E2XRTZ2zE4fKrAeh75XDCg&ct=result&id=dCkbAAAAIAAJ&dq=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&q=SARVAIYA+#search_anchor] Gujarat State Gazetteers: Amreli</ref><ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&q=jesar&dq=jesar&hl=en&ei=_n3RTYWfN8vLrQfE083CCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA] Gazetteer, 1884</ref>\n\nThe fort of ''Vejalkotha'' also known as ''Vejalkot'' is named after its founder Sarvaiya Vejoji who fought with troops of Sultan Mahmud Begda from there, which is located in [[Girnar]] on eastern bank of Raval river and is now an archaeological site of interest.<ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=K-fRTYO7OIrYrQeZ6r2_CQ&ct=result&id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&dq=SARVAIYA&q=vejalkotha#search_anchor]</ref><ref name=g>[http://www.archive.org/stream/archaeologicals00indigoog/archaeologicals00indigoog_djvu.txt List of Arohitiotural Structures and othir Remains in the Province of Kathuwad. 19. Vejalkot, N. of TJnft, and Khibra Darw&ja, of brick.] Archaeological Survey of Western India, 1865.</ref>\n\nSome archaeological evidence and inscriptions mentioning this facts have been found and unearthed like Hathsani inscription and others found among ruins of Vejalkot.<ref name=g/><ref name=t/>\n\nThey were thus reduced to small estate and village chiefs after they left Amreli and their old glory. However, till the time of independence, the princely state of Jesar, Hathsani, Datha and nearby estates were ruled by Sarvaiya Rajputs. The [[Jesar State]]  and [[Datha princely state]] along with other Princely States was merged into Union of India to form the [[United State of Kathiawar]].<ref name=t>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=PHBDAAAAYAAJ&q=SARVAIYA&dq=SARVAIYA&hl=en&ei=VOTRTZnkNMTxrQf2l9y0CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC4Q6AEwATge HATHSANI INSCRIPTION : HATHSANI is a separate tribute paying State held by some Sarvaiya Rajputs in Und-Sarvaiyawad, sub-division of the [[Gohelwad]] [[Prant]] in Kathiawar] Indian antiquary, Volume 15</ref><ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=c70MAAAAIAAJ&q=jesar&dq=jesar&hl=en&ei=_n3RTYWfN8vLrQfE083CCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAQ Jesar is situated in the Und sub-division of the Gohilvad district. It is about eight miles south-west of Chok thanah, sixteen miles southwest of Palitana, and twenty-four miles east of Kundla. The Grasias are Sarvaiyas Rajputs and trace their origin from Amreli Sarvaiyas, who it seems were Bhayad of Sarva]</ref>\n\n==Surname==\nSarvaiya, Sawaria surname is however found also among other castes of Gujarat like [[Prajapati]], [[Mestri (community)|Mestri]], [[Kadiya Kshatriya]].{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ra Navghan]], the ruler of [[Junagadh]] is a common ancestor of Sarvaiya, [[Raijada]] and Chudasama Rajput clans.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Rajput Groups|state=collapsed}}\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Lunar dynasty]]\n", "text_old": "{{use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{rewrite|date=February 2020}}\nThe '''Sarvaiya''' also spelled ''Sarvaiyya'', ''Sarvia'', ''Sarwia'' are a [[Rajput]] clan of India, mainly found in [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==History==\n\nAccording to the [[Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency]],The Sarvaiyas come from a branch of the [[Chudasama]]s, who are themselves a branch of the [[Samma (tribe)|Samma Rajput]]s. They ruled over Datha.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=State)|first=Bombay (India :|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&q=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&dq=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&hl=en&ei=E2XRTZ2zE4fKrAeh75XDCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAw#v=snippet&q=SARVAIYA%20CHUDASAMA&f=false|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency ...|date=1884|publisher=Government Central Press|language=en}}</ref> Among other estates that they ruled were [[Amreli]], Hathasnsi, [[Jesar]], [[Datha State|Datha]], [[Vasavad]],<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gujarat (India)|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=dCkbAAAAIAAJ|title=Gujarat State Gazetteers: Amreli|date=1972|publisher=Directorate of Government Print., Stationery and Publications, Gujarat State|language=en}}</ref> Santhli, Chital, [[Savarkundla|Kundla]],<ref name=b/> [[Bhavnagar|Gohilwad]], Chhatrasa, Chiroda, Chok, Pan, Ranigam,<ref name=c>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=Wr4MAAAAIAAJ&q=SARVAIYA&dq=SARVAIYA&hl=en&ei=qWTRTZWtEIjNrQf1xojDCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC4Q6AEwATgK] Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency, Volume 9, Part 1, 1901</ref> and other estates in [[Kathiawar]].<ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=CIoZAAAAYAAJ&q=SARVAIYA&dq=SARVAIYA&hl=en&ei=Z-PRTfqNGo6zrAexl4SiCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBA] Imperial gazetteer of India , 1908 by Sir William Wilson Hunter, [[Richard Burn (Indologist)|Sir Richard Burn]], Great Britain. India Office</ref>\n\nSarvaiya kingdom like the Chudasamas, were attacked in 1476 by Sultan [[Mahmud Begada]] . When Mahmud Begada, attacked Amreli, after taking over Junagadh from Chudasama, the Sarvaiya rulers of Amreli notably the two brothers Jesaji and Vejaji  for fighting against troops of Sultan Mahmud Begda, became outlaws, in order to re conquer Amreli.  Jesaji and Vejaji were able to get jagir of 64 villages from sultanate of Mohmud Begda  after fighting by remaining in outlawry for twelve years. Subsequently they settled in Hathasni. Later, the brothers divided the new estate between them, Jesoji receiving Hathasni and Vejoji estate of Jesar.<ref name=b>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=E2XRTZ2zE4fKrAeh75XDCg&ct=result&id=dCkbAAAAIAAJ&dq=SARVAIYA+CHUDASAMA&q=SARVAIYA+#search_anchor] Gujarat State Gazetteers: Amreli</ref><ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&q=jesar&dq=jesar&hl=en&ei=_n3RTYWfN8vLrQfE083CCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA] Gazetteer, 1884</ref>\n\nThe fort of ''Vejalkotha'' also known as ''Vejalkot'' is named after its founder Sarvaiya Vejoji who fought with troops of Sultan Mahmud Begda from there, which is located in [[Girnar]] on eastern bank of Raval river and is now an archaeological site of interest.<ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=K-fRTYO7OIrYrQeZ6r2_CQ&ct=result&id=pz3rFgOTkyUC&dq=SARVAIYA&q=vejalkotha#search_anchor]</ref><ref name=g>[http://www.archive.org/stream/archaeologicals00indigoog/archaeologicals00indigoog_djvu.txt List of Arohitiotural Structures and othir Remains in the Province of Kathuwad. 19. Vejalkot, N. of TJnft, and Khibra Darw&ja, of brick.] Archaeological Survey of Western India, 1865.</ref>\n\nSome archaeological evidence and inscriptions mentioning this facts have been found and unearthed like Hathsani inscription and others found among ruins of Vejalkot.<ref name=g/><ref name=t/>\n\nThey were thus reduced to small estate and village chiefs after they left Amreli and their old glory. However, till the time of independence, the princely state of Jesar, Hathsani, Datha and nearby estates were ruled by Sarvaiya Rajputs. The [[Jesar State]]  and [[Datha princely state]] along with other Princely States was merged into Union of India to form the [[United State of Kathiawar]].<ref name=t>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=PHBDAAAAYAAJ&q=SARVAIYA&dq=SARVAIYA&hl=en&ei=VOTRTZnkNMTxrQf2l9y0CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC4Q6AEwATge HATHSANI INSCRIPTION : HATHSANI is a separate tribute paying State held by some Sarvaiya Rajputs in Und-Sarvaiyawad, sub-division of the [[Gohelwad]] [[Prant]] in Kathiawar] Indian antiquary, Volume 15</ref><ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?id=c70MAAAAIAAJ&q=jesar&dq=jesar&hl=en&ei=_n3RTYWfN8vLrQfE083CCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAQ Jesar is situated in the Und sub-division of the Gohilvad district. It is about eight miles south-west of Chok thanah, sixteen miles southwest of Palitana, and twenty-four miles east of Kundla. The Grasias are Sarvaiyas Rajputs and trace their origin from Amreli Sarvaiyas, who it seems were Bhayad of Sarva]</ref>\n\n==Surname==\nSarvaiya, Sawaria surname is however found also among other castes of Gujarat like [[Prajapati]], [[Mestri (community)|Mestri]], [[Kadiya Kshatriya]].{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ra Navghan]], the ruler of [[Junagadh]] is a common ancestor of Sarvaiya, [[Raijada]] and Chudasama Rajput clans.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Rajput Groups|state=collapsed}}\n[[Category:Rajput clans of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Lunar dynasty]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ditto", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarvaiya"}
{"title_page": "Herbert Deveril", "text_new": "{{short description|Photographer (b. 1840l d. 1911)}}\n[[File:Gabriels Gully.jpg|thumb|Gold rush era image of [[Gabriel's Gully]], circa 1875]]\n[[File:Ngaikiha Te Raukura lying on the mahau.jpg|thumb|Maori woman on the porch of a [[wharepuni]], 1875]]\n\n'''Albert Edwin Ekins''' (9 May 1840 - 24 August 1911), known as '''Herbet Deveril''', was a photographer in Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://natlib.govt.nz/records/23192878|title=Deveril, Herbert, 1840-1911 :Parnell, Auckland|first=Herbert|last=Deveril|date=January 1, 1873|website=natlib.govt.nz}}</ref><ref name=NZLib>{{Cite web|url=https://natlib.govt.nz/records/22389366|title=Deveril, Herbert, 1840-1911|date=January 1, 1840|website=Deveril, Herbert, 1840-1911 &#124; Items &#124; National Library of New Zealand}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d50WXol9fOEC&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=Herbert+Deveril&source=bl&ots=y5_un0RepE&sig=ACfU3U0RvITXiX42gvqetdJAfIuTaFJXEg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP9PG8yqbmAhVOvFkKHYZtAKU4FBDoATALegQIFBAB#v=onepage&q=Herbert+Deveril&f=false|title=The Body in the Library|first1=Leigh|last1=Dale|first2=Simon|last2=Ryan|date=December 8, 1998|publisher=Rodopi|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h7UaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=Herbert+Deveril&source=bl&ots=20ZswID_qa&sig=ACfU3U18tD5V8xw4lYCx6OAzmPR8iwfq9Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP9PG8yqbmAhVOvFkKHYZtAKU4FBDoATANegQIFRAB#v=onepage&q=Herbert+Deveril&f=false|title=The Photographic Times|date=December 8, 1883|publisher=Scoville Manufacturing Company|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nAlbert Edwin Ekins was born in 9 May 1840 in [[Ware, Hertfordshire]], England, the son of George and Elizabeth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canterburyphotography.blogspot.com/2012/01/deveril-herbert.html|title=Early New Zealand Photographers: DEVERIL, Herbert|first=Early Canterbury|last=Photography}}</ref> He studied [[photolithography]] in [[Southampton]] before preparing for the [[Priesthood in the Catholic Church|priesthood]] in [[Belgium]]. He left  the church, changed his name to Herbert Deveril, and in 1864 emigrated to [[Australia]].<ref name=NZLib/> \n\nHe worked in a number of photographic studios and as a government photographer in [[Melbourne]], before moving to New Zealand in March 1873 where he worked as a government photographer.<ref>https://www.daao.org.au/bio/herbert-deveril/</ref>\n\nHe took photographs of sights in New Zealand for the [[Philadelphia Centennial Exhibition]], the first official [[World's Fair]] in 1876.{{cn|date=February 2020}} His work included photos of Maoris, [[Wairoa]] Bridge, [[Rotomahana]] hot springs,  [[Hot Lake District|Hot Lake]] district and [[Tauranga]].<ref>New Zealand Herald, Volume XIII, Issue 4548, 12 June 1876 page 2</ref><ref>New Zealand Herald, Volume XIII, Issue 4427, 22 January 1876, Page 2</ref>\n\nDeveril lived in [[Auckland]] until 1891, moving to South Africa, where he invested in ostrich farming. He later returned to Australia, and in 1901 moved to [[North Queensland]]. Deveril died 24 August 1911 in [[Townsville]] and is buried in the town's Belgian cemetery.\n\nThe [[Hocken Library]] at the [[University of Otago]] has held exhibitions of his work.<ref>Herbert Deveril Photographer, exhibition 1981</ref><ref>Exhibition Catalogue (Dunedin: Hocken Library, 1987)</ref> [[Auckland Art Gallery Toi o T\u0101maki]] holds a number of his photographs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aucklandartgallery.com/explore-art-and-ideas/artist/1210/herbert-deveril|title=Herbert Deveril|website=Auckland Art Gallery}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deveril, Herbert}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Ware, Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Australian photographers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand photographers]]\n[[Category:19th-century photographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Photographer (b. 1840l d. 1911)}}\n[[File:Gabriels Gully.jpg|thumb|Gold rush era image of [[Gabriel's Gully]], circa 1875]]\n[[File:Ngaikiha Te Raukura lying on the mahau.jpg|thumb|Maori woman on the porch of a [[wharepuni]], 1875]]\n\n'''Albert Edwin Ekins''' (9 May 1840 - 24 August 1911), known as '''Herbet Deveril''', was a photographer in Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://natlib.govt.nz/records/23192878|title=Deveril, Herbert, 1840-1911 :Parnell, Auckland|first=Herbert|last=Deveril|date=January 1, 1873|website=natlib.govt.nz}}</ref><ref name=NZLib>{{Cite web|url=https://natlib.govt.nz/records/22389366|title=Deveril, Herbert, 1840-1911|date=January 1, 1840|website=Deveril, Herbert, 1840-1911 &#124; Items &#124; National Library of New Zealand}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d50WXol9fOEC&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=Herbert+Deveril&source=bl&ots=y5_un0RepE&sig=ACfU3U0RvITXiX42gvqetdJAfIuTaFJXEg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP9PG8yqbmAhVOvFkKHYZtAKU4FBDoATALegQIFBAB#v=onepage&q=Herbert+Deveril&f=false|title=The Body in the Library|first1=Leigh|last1=Dale|first2=Simon|last2=Ryan|date=December 8, 1998|publisher=Rodopi|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h7UaAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=Herbert+Deveril&source=bl&ots=20ZswID_qa&sig=ACfU3U18tD5V8xw4lYCx6OAzmPR8iwfq9Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP9PG8yqbmAhVOvFkKHYZtAKU4FBDoATANegQIFRAB#v=onepage&q=Herbert+Deveril&f=false|title=The Photographic Times|date=December 8, 1883|publisher=Scoville Manufacturing Company|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nAlbert Edwin Ekins was born in 9 May 1840 in [[Ware, Hertfordshire]], England, the son of George and Elizabeth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canterburyphotography.blogspot.com/2012/01/deveril-herbert.html|title=Early New Zealand Photographers: DEVERIL, Herbert|first=Early Canterbury|last=Photography}}</ref> He studied [[photolithography]] in [[Southampton]] before preparing for the [[Priesthood in the Catholic Church|priesthood]] in [[Belgium]]. He left  the church, changed his name to Herbert Deveril, and in 1864 emigrated to [[Australia]].<ref name=NZLib/> \n\nHe worked in a number of photographic studios and as a government photographer in [[Melbourne]], before moving to New Zealand in March 1873 where he worked as a government photographer.<ref>https://www.daao.org.au/bio/herbert-deveril/</ref>\n\nHe took photographs of sights in New Zealand for the [[Philadelphia Centennial Exhibition]], the first official [[World's Fair]] in 1876.{{cn|date=February 2020}} His work included photos of Maoris, [[Wairoa]] Bridge, [[Rotomahana]] hot springs,  [[Hot Lake]] district and [[Tauranga]].<ref>New Zealand Herald, Volume XIII, Issue 4548, 12 June 1876 page 2</ref><ref>New Zealand Herald, Volume XIII, Issue 4427, 22 January 1876, Page 2</ref>\n\nDeveril lived in [[Auckland]] until 1891, moving to South Africa, where he invested in ostrich farming. He later returned to Australia, and in 1901 moved to [[North Queensland]]. Deveril died 24 August 1911 in [[Townsville]] and is buried in the town's Belgian cemetery.\n\nThe [[Hocken Library]] at the [[University of Otago]] has held exhibitions of his work.<ref>Herbert Deveril Photographer, exhibition 1981</ref><ref>Exhibition Catalogue (Dunedin: Hocken Library, 1987)</ref> [[Auckland Art Gallery Toi o T\u0101maki]] holds a number of his photographs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aucklandartgallery.com/explore-art-and-ideas/artist/1210/herbert-deveril|title=Herbert Deveril|website=Auckland Art Gallery}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deveril, Herbert}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Ware, Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Australian photographers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand photographers]]\n[[Category:19th-century photographers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHot Lake(link changed toHot Lake District) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbert_Deveril"}
{"title_page": "Church of Righteous John the Russian", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox church\n| denomination           = [[Russian Orthodox]]\n| name                   = Church of Righteous John the Russian in Kuntsevo\n| fullname               = {{Lang|ru|\u0425\u0440\u0430\u043c \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u041a\u0443\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432\u0435, \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430}}\n| image                  = \u041a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u044f\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c\u044b \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435.jpg\n| caption                = The church complex of Righteous John the Russian as viewed from the Yartsevskaya str.\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|55|44|3.95|N|37|24|19.32|E|display=inline,title}}\n| country                = Russia\n| location               = Moscow\n| website                = http://ioannrus.ru\n| founded date           = 2004\n| founder                = \n| dedication             = Saint John the Russian\n| consecrated date       = 7 July 2016\n| cult                   = \n| relics                 = \n| events                 = \n| status                 = Active\n| functional status      = \n| architect              = \n| architectural type     = \n| style                  = [[Russian church architecture|Russian traditional]]\n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      = \n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        = \n}}\n\n'''Church of Righteous John the Russian in Kuntsevo''' is an [[Orthodoxy|orthodox]] [[Temple|church]] in Moscow, Russia, in [[Kuntsevo]] district of [[Western Administrative Okrug]].\n[[File:\u041a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435.jpg|left|thumb|Stone church of Righteous John the Russian in Moscow. View from west.]]\nThe church belongs to the Deanery (''Blagochiniye'') of [[Saint George|St. George]], Western Vicariate, [[Urban Diocese of Moscow]] of [[Russian Orthodox Church]].\n\n== Church complex ==\nBy the blessing of [[Patriarch Alexy II of Moscow]] and all Rus' a small wooden [[Temple|church]] was erected in 2004, its architectural form being \"korablets\" (''[[Old Russian]]'': \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0446, \"a small ship\"), which is characteristic for [[Russian church architecture|old Russian wooden churches]] and represents the Church as a sanctuary from the storms of life.\n\nIn 2010 the [[Mayor of Moscow]] signed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mos.ru/authority/documents/doc/17918220|title=Authorities / Moscow City official site|website=www.mos.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref> an order to build a church complex, thus a tract of land to build a large stone church was assigned. The church became a part of the Program of Building of Orthodox Churches in Moscow (\"200 Churches\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/voiceofrussia/2012_04_18/72123418/|title=Program 200: church next door|website=sputniknews.com|access-date=2016-09-13}}</ref>).\n\n7 July 2016 the head of the Western Vicariate of Moscow [[Tikhon (Shevkunov)|Bishop Tikhon of Yegoryevsk]] [[Consecrations in Eastern Christianity|consecrated]] the erected church by the brief rite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m-blago.ru/publications/17-news/10189-maloe-osvyashhenie-xrama-sv-prav-ioanna-russkogo.html|title=Consecration of the Church of Righteous John the Russian by the Brief Rite|first=T.A.|last=Adamova|website=m-blago.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref>\n\n2 April 2017 Patriarch Kirill of Moscow and all Rus' consecrated the church by the great rite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.patriarchia.ru/db/text/4848668.html|title=\u0412 \u041d\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044e 5-\u044e \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0432\u044f\u0442\u0435\u0439\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445 \u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043b \u043e\u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u0438\u043b \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u0424\u0438\u043b\u0438-\u0414\u0430\u0432\u044b\u0434\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435 / \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 / \u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u044f.ru|website=\u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u044f.ru|language=ru|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe main altar of the church is consecrated in honour of Saint Righteous [[John the Russian]], the [[Confessor of Faith]]. Also there is a side-altar which is consecrated in honour of the [[Annunciation]].\n\nThe church keeps an icon of Righteous John the Russian with a piece of his [[relic]]s. The small wooden church is decorated with a wrought [[Melchior (alloy)|melchior]] [[iconostasis]] in basma technique, which blends [[Russian architecture|Old Russian traditions]] with some elements of [[Byzantine style]], and [[murals]].\n\n== Divine services and parish activities ==\nThe [[Church service|divine services]] are held daily \u2013 a [[Divine Liturgy|Liturgy]] at 8:30&nbsp;am (two Liturgies, at 7&nbsp;am and at 10&nbsp;am on Sundays, [[Great Feasts of the Orthodox Church|The Twelve Great Feasts]] and other great feasts), and an evening service at 5&nbsp;pm. All the kinds of occasional services are also administered: [[Moleben]]s, [[Memorial service (Orthodox)|Memorial services]], [[Marriage|Matrimonies]] and [[Baptisms]].\n[[File:Hram 2006.jpg|left|thumb|Small wooden church of Righteous John the Russian in Moscow. View from south.]]\n[[File:\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440 \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u041a\u0443\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432\u0435.jpg|left|thumb|Interior of small wooden church of Righteous John the Russian in Kuntsevo]]\nThe parish activities include a [[Sunday school]] for different ages with an [[amateur theatre]], handwork [[Club (organization)|clubs]], the Parus (''Russian:'' \"a sail\") [[Club (organization)|club]] of history and tourism for [[teenagers]], the Vernost (''Russian:'' \"fidelity\") [[List of youth organizations|union of Orthodox young adults]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.200hramov.ru/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=506&catid=1&Itemid=3|title=New Parishes Reveal the Living Beauty of the Church to Young People|website=www.200hramov.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref> a [[Christian pilgrimage|pilgrimage]] service, a [[social service]], a school of Orthodox [[home economics]], a video [[Lecture hall|lecture-hall]].\n\nThe [[priesthood]] and the [[social service]] of the church help the 15th [[Orphanage]] for children with growth [[Multiple abnormalities|abnormalities]], local state centers of [[social service]], parishioners in need and [[prisoners]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.miloserdie.ru/church/2227|title=Church of Righteous John the Russian in Kuntsevo, Moscow \u2013 Churches and monasteries \u2013 DB of social service|website=social.miloserdie.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref>\n[[File:\u041f\u0430\u043c\u044f\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0443 \u0420\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u044b \u0432 \u041a\u0443\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432\u0435.jpg|thumb|The monument of The Defender of Motherland]]\nOn 8 May 2015, the day before 60th anniversary of the [[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory]] in the [[Great Patriotic War]], upon an initiative of parishioners a monument of The Defender of Motherland was erected beside the church.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kuntsevo.mos.ru/presscenter/news/detail/1837753.html|title=Monument of the Defender of Motherland Unveiled in Kuntsevo|website=kuntsevo.mos.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref> The monument depicts a tired soldier in [[Second World War]] [[Soviet army]] [[uniform]], holding a [[PPSh-41]] with its [[Gun barrel|barrel]] pointing downwards, seemingly returning home after the [[Victory Day (9 May)|victory]] in [[World War II]].\n\n== Patronal feasts ==\n* Day of [[John the Russian|Saint Righteous John the Russian]], the Confessor of Faith \u2013  27 May ([[Julian calendar|JC]]) / 9 June ([[Gregorian calendar|GC]]).\n* [[Annunciation]] \u2013 25 March ([[Julian calendar|JC]]) / 7 April ([[Gregorian calendar|GC]]).\n\n== Priesthood of the Church ==\n* senior priest [[protoiereus]] Andrey Smirnov\n*protoiereus Mikhail Glazov\n* priest Dimitry Mazanov\n* [[deacon]] Boris Ivanov\n*deacon Arseniy Ivanchenko\n*deacon Ilya Yurin\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Russia|Christianity}}\n* [[John the Russian|Saint John the Russian]]\n* [[Kuntsevo District|Kuntsevo district of Moscow]]\n*[[List of churches in Moscow]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ioannrus.ru Official website {{in lang|ru}}]\n\n[[Category:Russian Orthodox churches in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox church buildings]]\n[[Category:Church buildings with domes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox church\n| denomination           = [[Russian Orthodox]]\n| name                   = Church of Righteous John the Russian in Kuntsevo\n| fullname               = {{Lang|ru|\u0425\u0440\u0430\u043c \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u041a\u0443\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432\u0435, \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430}}\n| image                  = \u041a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u044f\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c\u044b \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435.jpg\n| caption                = The church complex of Righteous John the Russian as viewed from the Yartsevskaya str.\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|55|44|3.95|N|37|24|19.32|E|display=inline,title}}\n| country                = Russia\n| location               = Moscow\n| website                = http://ioannrus.ru\n| founded date           = 2004\n| founder                = \n| dedication             = Saint John the Russian\n| consecrated date       = 7 July 2016\n| cult                   = \n| relics                 = \n| events                 = \n| status                 = Active\n| functional status      = \n| architect              = \n| architectural type     = \n| style                  = [[Russian church architecture|Russian traditional]]\n| groundbreaking         = \n| completed date         = \n| construction cost      = \n| closed date            = \n| demolished date        = \n}}\n\n'''Church of Righteous John the Russian in Kuntsevo''' is an [[Orthodoxy|orthodox]] [[Temple|church]] in Moscow, Russia, in [[Kuntsevo]] district of [[Western Administrative Okrug]].\n[[File:\u041a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435.jpg|left|thumb|Stone church of Righteous John the Russian in Moscow. View from west.]]\nThe church belongs to the Deanery (''Blagochiniye'') of [[Saint George|St. George]], Western Vicariate, [[Urban Diocese of Moscow]] of [[Russian Orthodox Church]].\n\n== Church complex ==\nBy the blessing of [[Patriarch Alexy II of Moscow]] and all Rus' a small wooden [[Temple|church]] was erected in 2004, its architectural form being \"korablets\" (''[[Old Russian]]'': \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0446, \"a small ship\"), which is characteristic for [[Russian church architecture|old Russian wooden churches]] and represents the Church as a sanctuary from the storms of life.\n\nIn 2010 the [[Mayor of Moscow]] signed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mos.ru/authority/documents/doc/17918220|title=Authorities / Moscow City official site|website=www.mos.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref> an order to build a church complex, thus a tract of land to build a large stone church was assigned. The church became a part of the Program of Building of Orthodox Churches in Moscow (\"200 Churches\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/voiceofrussia/2012_04_18/72123418/|title=Program 200: church next door|website=sputniknews.com|access-date=2016-09-13}}</ref>).\n\n7 July 2016 the head of the Western Vicariate of Moscow [[Tikhon (Shevkunov)|Bishop Tikhon of Yegoryevsk]] [[Consecrations in Eastern Christianity|consecrated]] the erected church by the brief rite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m-blago.ru/publications/17-news/10189-maloe-osvyashhenie-xrama-sv-prav-ioanna-russkogo.html|title=Consecration of the Church of Righteous John the Russian by the Brief Rite|first=T.A.|last=Adamova|website=m-blago.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref>\n\n2 April 2017 Patriarch Kirill of Moscow and all Rus' consecrated the church by the great rite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.patriarchia.ru/db/text/4848668.html|title=\u0412 \u041d\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044e 5-\u044e \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0432\u044f\u0442\u0435\u0439\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445 \u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043b \u043e\u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u0438\u043b \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u0424\u0438\u043b\u0438-\u0414\u0430\u0432\u044b\u0434\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435 / \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 / \u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u044f.ru|website=\u041f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u044f.ru|language=ru|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe main altar of the church is consecrated in honour of Saint Righteous [[John the Russian]], the [[Confessor of Faith]]. Also there is a side-altar which is consecrated in honour of the [[Annunciation]].\n\nThe church keeps an icon of Righteous John the Russian with a piece of his [[relic]]s. The small wooden church is decorated with a wrought [[Melchior (alloy)|melchior]] [[iconostasis]] in basma technique, which blends [[Russian architecture|Old Russian traditions]] with some elements of [[Byzantine style]], and [[murals]].\n\n== Divine services and parish activities ==\nThe [[Church service|divine services]] are held daily \u2013 a [[Divine Liturgy|Liturgy]] at 8:30&nbsp;am (two Liturgies, at 7&nbsp;am and at 10&nbsp;am on Sundays, [[Great Feasts of the Orthodox Church|The Twelve Great Feasts]] and other great feasts), and an evening service at 5&nbsp;pm. All the kinds of occasional services are also administered: [[Moleben]]s, [[Memorial service (Orthodox)|Memorial services]], [[Marriage|Matrimonies]] and [[Baptisms]].\n[[File:Hram 2006.jpg|left|thumb|Small wooden church of Righteous John the Russian in Moscow. View from south.]]\n[[File:\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440 \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043e\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432 \u041a\u0443\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432\u0435.jpg|left|thumb|Interior of small wooden church of Righteous John the Russian in Kuntsevo]]\nThe parish activities include a [[Sunday school]] for different ages with an [[amateur theatre]], handwork [[Club (organization)|clubs]], the Parus (''Russian:'' \"a sail\") [[Club (organization)|club]] of history and tourism for [[teenagers]], the Vernost (''Russian:'' \"fidelity\") [[List of youth organizations|union of Orthodox young adults]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.200hramov.ru/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=506&catid=1&Itemid=3|title=New Parishes Reveal the Living Beauty of the Church to Young People|website=www.200hramov.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref> a [[Christian pilgrimage|pilgrimage]] service, a [[social service]], a school of Orthodox [[home economics]], a video [[Lecture hall|lecture-hall]].\n\nThe [[priesthood]] and the [[social service]] of the church help the 15th [[Orphanage]] for children with growth [[Multiple abnormalities|abnormalities]], local state centers of [[social service]], parishioners in need and [[prisoners]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.miloserdie.ru/church/2227|title=Church of Righteous John the Russian in Kuntsevo, Moscow \u2013 Churches and monasteries \u2013 DB of social service|website=social.miloserdie.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref>\n[[File:\u041f\u0430\u043c\u044f\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0443 \u0420\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u044b \u0432 \u041a\u0443\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432\u0435.jpg|thumb|The monument of The Defender of Motherland]]\nOn 8 May 2015, the day before 60th anniversary of the [[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory]] in the [[Great Patriotic War]], upon an initiative of parishioners a monument of The Defender of Motherland was erected beside the church.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kuntsevo.mos.ru/presscenter/news/detail/1837753.html|title=Monument of the Defender of Motherland Unveiled in Kuntsevo|website=kuntsevo.mos.ru|access-date=2016-09-13|language=ru}}</ref> The monument depicts a tired soldier in [[Second World War]] [[Soviet army]] [[uniform]], holding a [[PPSh-41]] with its [[Gun barrel|barrel]] pointing downwards, seemingly returning home after the [[Victory Day (9 May)|victory]] in [[World War II]].\n\n== Patronal feasts ==\n* Day of [[John the Russian|Saint Righteous John the Russian]], the Confessor of Faith \u2013  27 May ([[Julian calendar|JC]]) / 9 June ([[Gregorian calendar|GC]]).\n* [[Annunciation]] \u2013 25 March ([[Julian calendar|JC]]) / 7 April ([[Gregorian calendar|GC]]).\n\n== Priesthood of the Church ==\n* senior priest [[protoiereus]] Andrey Smirnov\n*protoiereus Mikhail Glazov\n* priest Dimitry Mazanov\n* [[deacon]] Boris Ivanov\n*deacon Arseniy Ivanchenko\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Russia|Christianity}}\n* [[John the Russian|Saint John the Russian]]\n* [[Kuntsevo District|Kuntsevo district of Moscow]]\n*[[List of churches in Moscow]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ioannrus.ru Official website {{in lang|ru}}]\n\n[[Category:Russian Orthodox churches in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox church buildings]]\n[[Category:Church buildings with domes]]\n", "name_user": "Lexmirnov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePriesthood of the Church:added info", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Church_of_Righteous_John_the_Russian"}
